align=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Pledge to our flag, an ad for flag makers?</span><hr size=1> Vendrix, the argument is:<br>
<br>
Is the Pledge of Allegiance constitutional.<br>
<br>
I don't think it is and I've tried to demonstrate why I think it's not within the framework of our constitution.  Maybe I was using the term &quot;equality&quot; incorrectly, in this case I was specifically referring to equality of religious beliefs which is a very important principle of our country.  Arguments for free public housing, welfare etc, are interesting but they are separate from this argument.<br>
<br>
Of course, I have my own biases, I'm an atheist, I'm not the bit religious which makes it hard for me to understand why people get so bent out of shape about other people's religions in the first place.  I would never hate someone based solely on the God they worship, because I honestly don't care, but I know others do.  People hate other people for their religion all the time and the government should not serve to isolate or divide the country on the basis of religion.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hey, little Johnny didn't say &quot;under God&quot; during the Pledge of Allegiance! You don't believe in God, Johnny, you worship Allah or something?  I bet your daddy blew up the World Trade Center!&quot;<br>
<br>
Of course, that example is inflammatory hyperbole, but it still serves to illustrate the dangers of setting citizens apart in a Pledge that's only supposed to bring us together.  <br>
<br>
The founders of the country worked pretty hard to set up a government where everyone would be free of religious bias and yet religion is now continually encroaching on government, either by those endorsing prayer in school or additions to the Pledge of Allegiance like &quot;under God.&quot;<br>
<br>
Hey, I love this country, the fact that people can freely argue and debate and bring lawsuits about the Pledge of Allegiance, it's a beautiful thing.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/umahtanhonorshield.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mahtan Honorshield</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 378<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/28/02 10:35:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3442.topic&index=87>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Pledge to our flag, an ad for flag makers?</span><hr size=1> Skerry: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Well, first to the one who says he wouldn't be too keen on saying it since he is an agnostic...<br>
<br>
By that statement either you are NOT agnostic, or you don't know what it means, or you don't know what you are.<br>
<br>
Agnostic takes no stance on the existance or non-existance of a higher power, basically believing that you are not pretentious(sp?) enough to say you know what is going on. That is agnostic. Thus you wouldn't care about saying it.<br>
<br>
Atheist on the other hand would, as you would then have no subscription to any belief that any form of higher power exists.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Good definition of agnostic and atheist, however not of my motivation. I think it's more disrespectful, as a non-christian, to participate in christian prayers and rites than it would be to just go along and participate. Of course, there are no black and white in this. Saying &quot;under God&quot; in some sort of pledge would be less hypocritical than receiving sacrament, but I'd still feel a bit uncomfortable doing it.<br>
<br>
Oh, and I just remembered something I wanted to say earlier: Isn't it true that one of the proper and legal ways of destroying an american flag is to burn it? :-)<br>
<br>
Ah yes, Federal Flag Code, Title 36, of the U.S. Code, paragraphs 176. Here are some interesting subsections:<br>
<br>
(i) &quot;The flag should never be used for advertising purposes in any manner whatsoever. It should not be embroidered on such articles as cushions or handkerchiefs and the like, printed or otherwise impressed on paper napkins or boxes or anything that is designed for temporary use and discard.&quot;<br>
<br>
(j) &quot;No part of the flag should ever be used as a costume or athletic uniform. The flag represents a living country and is itself considered a living thing.&quot;<br>
<br>
(k) &quot;The flag, when it is in such condition that it is no longer a fitting emblem for display, should be destroyed in a dignified way, preferably by burning.&quot;<br>
<br>
I'm quite sure that (i) and (j) are violated a LOT...:-)<br>
